<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> Various <i>Psorothamnus </i>spp. occur in California deserts. The species in this alliance grow 1.5 to 2 m tall.  Most have grayish to whitish stems with spine-tipped branches. Flowers are arranged in loose clusters with lavender to deep indigo blue color. Young stems and fruits are gland-dotted, and plants emit a strong odor.  The genus was previously known as <i>Dalea</i>. <br/>
<br/>
Stands of this alliance occur along washes, upper bajadas, sandy basins, and low slopes. <i>Psorothamnus </i>spp. appear adapted to disturbance whether through flooding, shifting substrate, or otherwise. Stands may be dominated by one or more <i>Psorothamnus </i>spp.  While the ranges of the species are overlapping, <i>P. arborescens </i>occurs further north in the Mojave Desert while<i>P. schottii </i> occurs further south and into Mexico. Related stands of <i>Sarcobatus baileyi </i>occur with <i>P. arborescens</i>. However, more sampling and analysis is needed in the southern Mojave, Colorado and Sonoran deserts to better evaluate relationships of <i>Psorothamnus </i>spp. stands in these regions. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
