    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p><i>Psorothamnus</i> spp. occur in the southern Mojave, Colorado, and Sonoran deserts of California.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ad). Stands occur along intermittent washes in the northern Mojave Desert including Owens Valley and Death Valley National Park, and they are likely to occur in the central Mojave (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dh-j). Stands occur near Fish Slough on intermittently flooded uplands (VegCAMP 2014b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er). Stands occur near Big Pine on lower volcanic slopes in recently disturbed post-fire sites.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-c). Stands occur on dune aprons and alluvial fans in Eureka Valley, Last Chance Range, and Saline Range (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Psorothamnus </i>spp. are thought to be poisonous to livestock. Native Americans utilized the roots  and stems of this genus for various treatments including gastrointestinal issues, toothaches, and influenza. They also used the flowers for dyes (Dole and Rose 1996). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Associations</h4>
        
            
            <ul class="text">
                
                    <li>Psorothamnus arborescens [1], [3]</li>
                
                    <li>Psorothamnus arborescens - Atriplex confertifolia - Tetradymia spp. [2], [3]</li>
                
                    <li>Psorothamnus polydenius - (Psorothamnus arborescens) [2], [3]</li>
                
                    <li>Psorothamnus polydenius var. polydenius / Achnatherum hymenoides [1]</li>
                
                    <li>Sarcobatus baileyi [3]</li>
                
            </ul>
        
    </div>

    
